<h1> Attorney General Ellison shuts down fraudulent student-loan debt-settlement company</h1>


<p class="lede">California-based company offering fraudulent âforgivenessâ scheme will pay State $15K to refund Minnesota consumers
</p>



</p>


<p align="left"><strong>October 7, 2022 (SAINT PAUL)</strong> â Minnesota Attorney General Keith Ellison announced today that his office has obtained a <a href="https://www.ag.state.mn.us/Office/Communications/2022/docs/StudentAidGroup_AoD.pdf" target="_blank">settlement</a> that requires a California student-loan debt-relief company that illegally collected fees from customers and misrepresented its services to consumers to cease operating in Minnesota and provide full refunds to its Minnesota consumers.Â Â  </p>

<p align="left">Among other things, Total Rain, Inc., doing business as Student Aid Group â a company based in Irvine, California â is alleged to have falsely promised consumers student-loan forgiveness, when only the federal government can forgive federal student loans.Â Â In reality, the Attorney General alleges that all the company did was enroll consumers in federal repayment programs that consumers can enroll themselves in for free, then pocketed both initial and monthly fees for doing so. It also collected its fees up front before performing the promised services, which is <a href="https://www.revisor.mn.gov/statutes/cite/332B.09" target="_blank">illegal under Minnesota law</a> regulating debt settlement services. Additionally, Student Aid Group was operating without registering as a debt-settlement service provider, as <a href="https://www.revisor.mn.gov/statutes/cite/332B.03" target="_blank">required by Minnesota law</a>.  </p>

<p align="left">The <a href="https://www.ag.state.mn.us/Office/Communications/2022/docs/StudentAidGroup_AoD.pdf" target="_blank">settlement</a>, filed in Ramsey County District Court, requires Student Aid Group to immediately pay the State $15,325 â the full amount it has collected from Minnesota customers âÂ Â which the Attorney General&rsquo;s Office will use to provide full restitution to consumers. The settlement also requires Student Aid Group to cease operating in Minnesota unless and until it registers as a debt-settlement service provider.Â Â Attorney General Ellison&rsquo;s Office alleges in the settlement that Student Aid Group violated Minnesota&rsquo;s <a href="https://www.revisor.mn.gov/statutes/cite/332B" target="_blank">Debt Services Settlement Act</a>, <a href="https://www.revisor.mn.gov/statutes/cite/325F.69" target="_blank">Prevention of Consumer Fraud Act</a>, and <a href="https://www.revisor.mn.gov/statutes/cite/325D.44" target="_blank">Uniform Deceptive Trade Practices Act</a>.  </p>

<p align="left">&ldquo;Minnesotans take out student loans in good faith so they can get educations that will help them better afford their lives. My office is showing once again that when companies take advantage of that good faith to rip Minnesotans off, we will come after them,&rdquo; Attorney General Ellison said. &ldquo;I encourage any Minnesotan who&rsquo;s been preyed upon by this company or others like it to contact my office so we can hold these bad actors accountable.&rdquo; </p>

<p align="left">Student-loan debt-relief companies often charge consumers hundreds or thousands of dollars of illegal upfront fees to enroll them in repayment plans or consolidation loans that all eligible federal student-loan borrowers can apply for on their own for free through the United States Department of Education. Often, these companies deceive consumers into believing that the fees will go toward paying down the consumers&rsquo; student-loan debt, when the companies actually pocket the fees.Â Â   </p>

<p align="left">Attorney General Ellison encourages anyone who has been victimized by Student Aid Group or any student-loan debt-relief company to <strong>contact the Minnesota Attorney General&rsquo;s Office</strong> by callingÂ (651) 296-3353 (Metro area) or (800) 657-3787 (Greater Minnesota), or by <a href="https://www.ag.state.mn.us/office/Forms/ConsumerAssistanceRequest.asp" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" data-auth="NotApplicable" data-safelink="true" data-linkindex="10">submitting a complaint online</a>.Â Â Â  </p>

<p align="left">The Attorney General&rsquo;s Office encourages borrowers to visit its website for additional information on how to avoid student-loan scams, including a publication entitled <a href="https://www.ag.state.mn.us/Consumer/Publications/StudentLoanAssistanceScams.asp" target="_blank">Student Loan Assistance Companies that Charge High Fees for What You Can Do for Free</a>.Â Student-loan borrowers may access the <a href="https://studentaid.gov/manage-loans/repayment/plans" target="_blank">United States Department of Education&rsquo;s website</a> for additional information about federal student-loan repayment programs available to allÂ eligible borrowers for free.Â   </p>

	
	
